Cars4U Case Study - Connie Xavier¶

Problem Definition and Information¶

Context¶

There is a huge demand for pre-owned cars over new cars in the Indian Market, as used car sales have surpassed new car sales in the last few years. Used cars have more uncertainty in pricing and supply over new cars. Understanding the factors that affect pricing is important as the pre-owned market grows.

As a senior data scientist at Cars4U, I have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing.

Objective¶

To analyze, visualize, and preprocess the data, build a linear regression model to predict the price of used cars, and gather insights and recommendations for the business.

Key Questions¶

  1. What are the key factors influencing the price of a used car?
  2. Is there a good linear regression model for the price of a used car? What does the performance assessment look like for such a model?

Data Information¶

Each record in the database represents attributes of a used car sold. A detailed data dictionary can be found below.

Data Dictionary

  • S.No.: Serial number
  • Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase
  • Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers (a unit used to measure length or distance) driven in the car by the previous owner(s)
  • Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner: Type of ownership
  • Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats: The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  • Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

# convert Mileage column to numeric
def tonumeric(var):
    if isinstance(var, str):  # checking if the value is string or not
        return float(
            var.lower().strip().split()[0]
        )  # splitting the value by space and taking the first part
    else:
        return np.nan  # will return NaN if value is not string


df["Mileage"] = df["Mileage"].apply(tonumeric)

In [2011]:
# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

It's uncommon and unlikely that cars will reach 325,000 km+ in their lifetime, but it really depends on many factors like how well the car is maintained. We can use the interquartile range as our cutoff point for outliers.

In [2033]:
# find the values that are greater than 4*IQR from the median
quartiles = np.quantile(
    df2["Kilometers_Driven"][df2["Kilometers_Driven"].notnull()], [0.25, 0.75]
)
km_4iqr = 4 * (quartiles[1] - quartiles[0])
outlier_km = df2.loc[
    np.abs(df2["Kilometers_Driven"] - df2["Kilometers_Driven"].median()) > km_4iqr,
    "Kilometers_Driven",
]
print(outlier_km.sort_values(ascending=False).count() / df2.shape[0] * 100, "%")
df2.loc[outlier_km.sort_values().index]

# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Part 4: Conclusions and Recommendations¶

Summary/Insights¶

Data Background:

  • There are 7253 rows and 14 columns in the data.
  • The Mileage, Engine, Power, Seats, and Price columns have null values.
  • The dependent variable, Price, is of float type.
  • The other numeric columns are S. No., Year, Kilometers_Driven, Seats, and New_Price.
  • All other columns are of object datatype.

Data Preprocessing:

  • The S.No. column was dropped as it isn’t important to the analysis.
  • The missing values in the target variable were dropped.
  • Mileage, Engine, and Power were converted to numeric datatypes after dropping the units.
  • Fuel, Transmission, and Owner_type were converted to category datatypes.
  • The Make column was created by extracting the make from the Name column.
  • Outliers in the Price column were dropped after plotting the boxplot and comparing the New_Price with the used car price.
  • Outliers in the Kilometers_Driven column were defined by the values greater than 4*IQR from the median. These outliers were dropped.
  • Outliers in Mileage column were defined by the 0 values. These were replaced based on the average mileage by vehicle make.
  • Outliers in the Power and Engine column were defined by comparing the values in the two columns since they are highly correlated. The outliers were replaced by Google search of the true value.
  • Outliers in the Seats column were defined by the 0 values. This was replaced via a Google search.
  • The car with the highest New_Price was dropped from the data as it was an outlier compared to the rest of the data.
  • Missing values in columns Mileage, Engine, Power, and Seats were imputed based on other cars with the same Name.
  • The remaining missing data in the Mileage column was imputed based on the average mileage by vehicle make or dropped.
  • Remaining missing data in the Power column was imputed based on the median power in the Engine column.
  • Remaining missing values were dropped.
  • Name column was dropped.
  • Log transformations were done on the Kilometers_Driven, Engine, Power, New_Price, and Price (in rupees) columns since the data was right-skewed.
  • Standard scaling was done on the Year and Mileage columns.
  • Power variable was dropped from the analysis due to its co-linearity with other variables.
  • Dummy variables were obtained for the categorical variables.

Observations from EDA:

  • The Price, Kilometers_Driven, Engine, Power, and New_Price variables are skewed to the right.
  • The Year variable is skewed to the left.
  • The Mileage variable is approximately normally distributed.
  • Most cars have 5 seats, are located in Mumbai, have diesel fuel type, manual transmission, first ownership, and Maruti make.
  • The Price column is highly correlated with New_Price, Power, and Engine columns
  • Power and New_Price are highly correlated.
  • Power and Engine columns are highly correlated with each other.
  • Car manufactured more recently sell for higher.
  • The median price is lowest for Jaipur, Pune, and Kolkata.
  • CNG and LPG are the least expensive cars.
  • Cars with one owner are more expensive than those which have had two or more owners.
  • Automatic cars are priced higher than manual cars.
  • Cars with 9 or 10 seats have the lowest median price.
  • Porsche and Land Rover have the highest median prices, while Chevrolet and Ambassador have the lowest median prices of used cars.

Model Building and Performance:

Three linear regression models were created to predict the log(price) of used cars: one basic model with all null values dropped, one pre-processed model, and one pre-processed model with polynomial features.

The pre-processed model without polynomial features performed the best with only 15 features chosen as part of step-forward feature selection. The chosen model performed similarly on the training and test data.

Recommendations¶

  • The price of a used car is highly correlated with the new price, power, and engine of a car, though these variables are also correlated with each other
  • The most important features in building a linear regression model of the data are: 
     'Kilometers_Driven_log', 'Engine_log', 'New_Price_log', 'Year_std',
 'Location_Bangalore', 'Location_Coimbatore', 'Location_Hyderabad',
 'Location_Kolkata', 'Fuel_Type_Petrol', 'Transmission_Manual',
 'Make_chevrolet', 'Make_mahindra', 'Make_maruti', 'Make_skoda',
 'Make_tata'
  • A linear regression model was successfully built that can be used by Cars4U to predict the log(price) of a used car with an adjusted R^2 of around 0.93 and RMSE of 0.23. 93% of the variance in the price is explained by the regression model. The RMSE is a measure of regression fit.
  • It is recommended that the business gather more data on other features like the type of car, its current condition, or accident history to see how these may influence performance.
  • Some categories like electric vehicles, or cars with three or more owners are a very small part of the data. It is recommended to gather more data from these categories to better predict the price of cars in these categories.
